==After the season==
Nebraska finished in 2nd place in the Big 12 North Division and tied for 4th conference-wide, with a final record of 10-3 (5-3). Prior to the season, Head Coach Frank Solich was feeling pressure to perform after a 7-7 (3-5) record the previous year (the first non-winning season since 1961), and had significantly revamped his coaching staff for 2003.

Despite the sweeping changes and the improvements they brought, which helped Nebraska to another 9-win season, Solich was fired at the conclusion of the regular season.  Defensive Coordinator [[Bo Pelini]] was named Interim Head Coach and led the Huskers to a 17-3 Alamo Bowl win over Michigan State.  When new Head Coach [[Bill Callahan (American football)|Bill Callahan]] was announced in later weeks, most of the existing assistants (including Pelini) were also fired.

Pelini would later return as Callahan's replacement in 2008.

